06430nam a22009855i 9781487517250DE-B159720210526051534.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210526t20202020onc    fo  d z      eng d  a97814875172507 a10.3138/97814875172502doi  a(DE-B1597)565865  a(OCoLC)1137372438  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  aonccCA-ON 4aBD450 7aSOC0020102bisacsh04a301.0122300aCapturing the Ineffable :bAn Anthropology of Wisdom /ced. by Philip Y. Kao, Joseph S. Alter. 1aToronto : bUniversity of Toronto Press, c[2020] 4c©2020  a1 online resource (264 p.) :b2 figures  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: Towards an Anthropology of Wisdom -- tPart One: Seeking Wisdom -- t1. Revelations of Delusion: Becoming Isomorphic to the Urgrund with Philip K. Dick -- t2. The Social Life of the Inexpressible: English Benedictine Mysticism, the Ineffable, and the Sublime -- tPart Two: Discerning Wisdom -- t3. How Wisdom Is Discovered: Discretion and Emotional Insights in Naikan Meditation in Japan -- t4. Navigating Wisdom and Time: Reflections on Aging and Eldercare -- tPart Three: Transmitting Wisdom -- t5. Yoga and Wisdom: Reflections on the Body at the Intersection of Epistemology and Ontology -- t6. Social Construction of Wisdom in Institutions -- tPart Four: Narrating Wisdom -- t7. Of Uncertainty, Sophiology, and Governance: Zen and the Art of Scenario Planning -- t8. Grappling with the Ineffable in Three African Situations: An Ethnographic Approach -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aGrounded in ethnographic case studies that examine experiences from which wisdom emerges, Capturing the Ineffable provides a rigorous analysis of the sociocultural context of wisdom in the contemporary world. Each chapter in the volume deals with different aspects and showcases how communities in different contexts — nursing homes, religious organizations, corporations, and monastic institutions, for example — engage with the ineffability of wisdom. Contributors draw from a range of disciplines and cross-cultural and historical data in order to interpret the meaning and value of wisdom as a human endeavour. This book also represents an anthropological method for evaluating various philosophical and scientific approaches to understanding wisdom, including how wisdom is learned and taught. Readers will be able to appreciate how action, emotion, uncertainty, and cultural systems come to bear on wisdom as a value in human life and expression. In the end, Capturing the Ineffable reveals how the conception and paradoxical nature of wisdom dispels the dichotomies of self/other, structure/agency, known/unknown, nature/culture, and the like. What is at stake is a recasting of wisdom as a particular kind of anthropological endeavour and, thus, a return to and modification of philosophical anthropology.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mai 2021) 0aAnthropology. 0aWisdom. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh  aaging.  aanthropology.  acommunities.  aconsciousness.  aculture.  aepistemic.  aepistemology.  aethnography.  ahealing.  aknowledge.  aphilosophical.  awisdom.1 aAlter, Joseph S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAlter, Joseph S., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBinsbergen, Wim M.J. Van, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChilson, Clark, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDoyle, Richard, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFaubion, James D., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/rela